				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/univine" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(276792); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=276792&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225791" alt="Univine" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=276792)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/univine" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(276792); return false;" >Univine</a></span> <span class="odate time_1484794511 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Jan 2017 02:55</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2729423">
									

<p>I have to say, I really enjoyed reading your proposal! The way you combined all of the different alternate-history SCPs into a coherent narrative was pretty effective, and I enjoyed reading the different worldviews and great power politics in the O5 messages.</p>
<p>I liked how you how included SCP-2515, which generally fits my view of SCP-2515 as a &quot;fragment&quot; of an alternate history. Your interpretation of the Europa statue is a bit different from mine, though, since I intended it to be a symbol for Mekhanism, not as an actual depiction of a god. Similarly, I intended Neo-Gnosticism to be a name of a cultural movement applied in retrospect similar to Neoclassicism. Granted, SCP-2515 didn't make either of those things very clear, so I can roll with your interpretation.</p>
<p>A nitpick: It looks like you're using the Wade-Giles Romanization for some of the Chinese names, and Pinyin for others (Taisuijing, Hong Xiuquan, Taiping, and Jindandao). Given the historical time period you're depicting, it might make sense to change the ones that use Pinyin to Wade-Giles for consistency.</p>

							</div>

								
