					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mrwrong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2039383); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2039383&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225791" alt="MrWrong" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2039383)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mrwrong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2039383); return false;" >MrWrong</a></span> <span class="odate time_1484795410 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Jan 2017 03:10</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2729434">
									

<blockquote>
<p>I liked how you how included SCP-2515, which generally fits my view of SCP-2515 as a &quot;fragment&quot; of an alternate history. Your interpretation of the Europa statue is a bit different from mine, though, since I intended it to be a symbol of Mekhanism, not as an actual depiction of a god. Similarly, I intended Neo-Gnosticism to be a name of a cultural movement applied in retrospect similar to Neoclassicism. Granted, SCP-2515 didn't make either of those things very clear, so I can roll with your interpretation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Do know that SCP-2515 was a major influence for this article, I just want to let you know.</p>
<p>I originally wanted to make it clear that Napoleon became a Mekhanist (the reference to clockwork soldiers is a remnant of it). However, I noticed that it was not explicit in SCP-2515 and decided to not be explicit (so that it makes sense with SCP-2515). From the O5's perspective, they perceive it as Europa worship (like the normal people of Europe then) and they could not figure out that it refers to a Broken God in reality.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>A nitpick: It looks like you're using the Wade-Giles Romanization for some of the Chinese names, and Pinyin for others (Taisuijing, Hong Xiuquan, Taiping, and Jindandao)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I was originally hesitant since 'Nanking' and 'Peking' is not derived from Wade-Giles, but from postal romanisation (which is slightly different). I ended up with Pinyin since it would be more recognisable to the audience (and thus, can be Googled).</p>
<p>If I can find a way to convert to postal romanisation, that would be ideal (for place names at least). But I will consider Wade-Giles for non-places.</p>

							</div>

								
					
